><p><span>Today I spoke with </span><div class=3D"profile-hover-card-target=
 profileHoverCardTarget-PBxvGm"><a class=3D"mention-pnpTE1" href=3D"https:/=
/open.substack.com/users/6319739-richard-hanania?utm_source=3Dmentions" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" data-attrs=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Richa=
rd Hanania&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:6319739,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;user&quot;,&=
quot;url&quot;:null,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/ima=
ge/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-pos=
t-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2de4c8df-7f9c-4bca-901c-53a83a=
3e97eb_2736x1824.jpeg&quot;,&quot;uuid&quot;:&quot;3b389a57-b521-4f48-ab3e-=
3ad57ec9e5c8&quot;}" data-component-name=3D"MentionUser">Richard Hanania</a=
></div><span> about the first 6 episodes of </span><em>The White Lotus</em>=
<span>.</span></p><p>Some topics we cover:</p><ul><li><p>Why middle-aged wo=
men partying in Thailand is more interesting than watching middle-aged men =
do the same thing. An equivalent trio of 3 successful 45 year old men would=
 simply buy the experience they wanted; but even rich and successful women =
still seek to be courted and desired.</p></li><li><p>In an intriguing rever=
sal, Lochlan, not Saxon, is the true predator in the show=E2=80=99s strange=
 sibling-power dynamic.</p></li><li><p>We talk about Lochlan possibly fakin=
g being blackout drunk=E2=80=94was he scheming all along? I explain how the=
 series cleverly flips expectations around =E2=80=9Ctoxic masculinity=E2=80=
=9D and subverts who we think holds the power.</p></li><li><p><span>We disc=
uss how </span><em>White Lotus</em><span> uses ambiguity and plausible deni=
ability to keep the audience guessing about intent and consent. Exploring t=
he deeper themes of shame, guilt, and sibling rivalry=E2=80=94and how they =
play out through sexual power plays.</span></p></li><li><p>I share how this=
 whole arc reminded me of a wild Dan Savage column that also involved strat=
egic intoxication and manipulation.</p></li><li><p>Did the Buddhist monk co=
nvince Tim to kill himself? =E2=80=9CYou cannot outrun pain.=E2=80=9D </p><=
/li><li><p>Breaking down Jacqueline=E2=80=99s power play and why it hit Lau=
rie so hard=E2=80=94this was about more than just sleeping with Laurie=E2=
=80=99s romantic interest.</p></li><li><p>There=E2=80=99s a subtle but hila=
rious scene where Gaitok walks right past Tim and Victoria after stealing t=
he gun, and they don't even clock him. Gaitok was so paranoid that they wou=
ld catch him but he was just another Thai hotel worker to them, completely =
invisible.</p></li><li><p><span>We go deep into that wild monologue from Fr=
ank (Sam Rockwell=E2=80=99s character) about wanting to be an Asian girl. R=
ichard and I did some homework and read chapter 9 of psychologist J. Michae=
l Bailey=E2=80=99s book about homosexuality and transsexuals. You can </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://faculty.wcas.northwestern.edu/JMichael-Bailey/autogyne=
philia.htm" rel=3D"">read it here</a><span>.</span></p></li><li><p>Explaini=
ng the concept of autogynephilia (men who are sexually aroused at the thoug=
ht of dressing in women=E2=80=99s clothes and being a woman) =E2=80=94what =
it is, where the theory came from, and how White Lotus snuck it into this s=
eason in a way most viewers missed.</p></li><li><p>We dive into the differe=
nce between "I have a female soul" and "I'm just a narcissistic man who wan=
ts to have sex with myself." One is socially acceptable. The other is proba=
bly true more often than people want to admit. There's a weird racial twist=
 to Frank=E2=80=99s identity fantasy that makes it even more psychologicall=
y fascinating.</p></li><li><p>I accept that autogynephilia is more nature t=
han nurture, but ask some questions about how it=E2=80=99s possible that me=
n could be =E2=80=9Cinnately=E2=80=9D sexually aroused by relatively modern=
 inventions (e.g., bras, high heels, etc.). I pose a thought experiment: wh=
at would an autogynephile look like if they were raised in a totally differ=
ent culture with different beauty standards?</p></li><li><p><span>We talk a=
bout Dr. Ben Carson=E2=80=99s </span><a href=3D"https://www.politico.com/st=
ory/2015/03/ben-carson-gay-choice-prison-115744" rel=3D"">infamous claim</a=
><span> that being gay is a choice, citing prison as an example=E2=80=94and=
 why, actually, he may have been onto something more than people gave him c=
redit for.</span></p></li><li><p>We talk about the growing tension with all=
 the guns floating around=E2=80=94Rick has one, Gaitok has one, Valentin=E2=
=80=99s crew probably does too. There=E2=80=99s no way this ends peacefully=
. </p></li><li><p>I suggest the plausibility of a White Lotus =E2=80=9CChek=
hov=E2=80=99s Blender=E2=80=9D moment=E2=80=94Saxon=E2=80=99s constant prot=
ein shakes might actually mask the sound of a gunshot in the final episode.=
</p></li><li><p><span>We wrap with a broader reflection on Thailand as a se=
tting=E2=80=94how </span><em>White Lotus</em><span> handles Western tourism=
 and cultural tropes without falling into caricature.</span></p></li></ul><=
